'''''Space Jockey''''' is a [[scrolling shooter]] designed by [[Garry Kitchen]] for the Atari VCS (renamed to the [[Atari 2600]] later in the year). It was published under the Vidtec brand of [[U.S. Games]] in 1982 as the initial release from the company.{{sfn|Bloom|1982|p=16}}  The game shipped on a 2K cartridge at a time when most VCS games were 4K.{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2014|ref=RetroGamer}}

''Space Jockey'' was the first video game designed by [[Garry Kitchen]]. He went on to program the 2600 port of ''[[Donkey Kong (arcade game)|Donkey Kong]]''.{{sfn|Hickey, Jr.|2020|p=25}}

==Gameplay==
[[File:Space-jockey-game-capture.gif|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot of ''Space Jockey''.]]
The player controls an "attack saucer" that flies to the right over scrolling, undulating terrain. The saucer only moves vertically and stops just before it hits the ground. The goal is to shoot ground-based tanks and flying enemies: jet planes, propeller planes, helicopters, and [[hot air balloon]]s.{{sfn|U.S. Games Coproration|1982|ref=manual}}Trees and houses appear on the ground as obstacles which can also be destroyed.
