''Space Jockey'' was released in January 1982.{{sfn|Bloom|1982|p=16}} According to a 2013 interview with Kitchen, ''Space Jockey'' sold over a million copies, but he believes most of those were at a discount.{{sfn|Fisher|2013|p=92}} A February 1983 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' article on retailers lowering game prices mentioned, "US Games recently sold off one of its older hits, the 2K ''Space Jockey'', at rock bottom prices through its distributors."{{sfn|Sweeting|1983|p=3}}{{sfn|Sweeting|1983|p=60}}

Dan Gutman reviewed ''Space Jockey'' in the December 1982 issue of ''[[Electronic Fun with Computers & Games]]''. Gutman compared the game to ''[[Defender (1981 video game)|Defender]]'' (1981) and ''[[Chopper Command]]'' (1982) saying that "there is nothing meaty here [...] but that doesn't mean it's bad" and that the game was "a pure test of your reaction time and doesn't pretend to be anything more."{{sfn|Gutman|1982|pp=62-63}} ''Space Jockey'' was one of three runners-up for the "Best Science Fiction/Fantasy Videogame" category in the 1983 Arcade Awards.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The 1983 Arcade Awards |journal=Arcade Express |date=November 7, 1982 |volume=1 |issue=7 |url=https://archive.org/details/arcade_express_v1n7/page/n3}}</ref>

From retrospective reviews, Brett Alan Weiss of online game database [[RhythmOne#AllGame|AllGame]] declared the game to be "a simplistic but enjoyable shooter."{{sfn|Weiss}}

